WEBVTT

1
00:00:15.760 --> 00:00:16.390
[Claire] Previously...

2
00:00:17.930 --> 00:00:20.980
I cannot admit there's
anything to do...

3
00:00:22.020 --> 00:00:23.390
but go on.

4
00:00:23.560 --> 00:00:26.110
[Jamie] That will be where
the new house will stand.

5
00:00:26.520 --> 00:00:28.900
We will make it
back here one day.

6
00:00:29.610 --> 00:00:32.950
-Won't we?
-Aye. We will.

7
00:00:33.110 --> 00:00:34.950
[soft music plays]

8
00:00:35.070 --> 00:00:38.200
Allow me to introduce
William Buccleigh MacKenzie.

9
00:00:38.370 --> 00:00:39.410
Your servant. Madam.

10
00:00:39.580 --> 00:00:41.370
T'was at Craigh na Dun.

11
00:00:41.500 --> 00:00:42.750
And here I am.

12
00:00:42.910 --> 00:00:43.750
Rob Cameron.

13
00:00:43.910 --> 00:00:45.920
He did it. Rob took Jem.

14
00:00:46.080 --> 00:00:47.210
-[gunshot]
-[yelps]

15
00:00:47.380 --> 00:00:48.710
It's Rob!

16
00:00:48.840 --> 00:00:49.880
Callahan!

17
00:00:50.050 --> 00:00:51.090
Brianna!

18
00:00:51.210 --> 00:00:52.760
[Brianna]
So. where do we belong now?

19
00:00:52.920 --> 00:00:56.390
So it's not a question
of where we belong; it's when.

20
00:00:56.550 --> 00:00:58.600
[Lord John]
Your son is due home shortly.

21
00:00:59.890 --> 00:01:01.020
Son?

22
00:01:01.180 --> 00:01:04.810
What we really want
is your protection.

23
00:01:05.310 --> 00:01:06.730
Where's Jane?

24
00:01:06.900 --> 00:01:09.440
Major Jenkins said that
she killed Captain Harkness

25
00:01:09.610 --> 00:01:11.230
and dragged her away.

26
00:01:11.650 --> 00:01:13.150
[Jamie] We need to go.

27
00:01:15.110 --> 00:01:16.860
You can come and live
with us on the Ridge.

28
00:01:17.200 --> 00:01:18.280
You'll be safe.

29
00:01:18.410 --> 00:01:19.700
Who was thy wife?

30
00:01:20.120 --> 00:01:21.370
Her name is Wahionhaweh.

31
00:01:21.490 --> 00:01:23.830
Emily chose me. but. Rachel.

32
00:01:23.950 --> 00:01:27.370
with my whole soul.
I choose you.

33
00:01:27.750 --> 00:01:30.090
[Rachel] A place where...

34
00:01:30.250 --> 00:01:31.710
we could raise our family.

35
00:01:33.250 --> 00:01:34.510
You mean...?

36
00:01:34.670 --> 00:01:37.640
♪ ♪

37
00:01:40.390 --> 00:01:42.720
I have had carnal knowledge
of your wife.

38
00:01:43.810 --> 00:01:45.770
Henry and Ben will be fighting
across the sea.

39
00:01:46.190 --> 00:01:47.480
Do you want to have
to tell your wife

40
00:01:47.650 --> 00:01:49.520
that your sons
have died in a war

41
00:01:49.690 --> 00:01:52.190
-that could have been stopped?
-[gunfire]

42
00:01:52.360 --> 00:01:53.360
[screaming]

43
00:01:53.530 --> 00:01:56.450
[tense music plays]

44
00:01:56.610 --> 00:01:57.860
♪ ♪

45
00:01:58.030 --> 00:01:58.740
[gasps]

46
00:01:58.910 --> 00:02:00.370
I'll do my best by thee.

47
00:02:02.240 --> 00:02:03.450
Can we go home?

48
00:02:04.290 --> 00:02:05.960
You're not going back
to the army?

49
00:02:06.120 --> 00:02:07.040
No.

50
00:02:07.210 --> 00:02:08.830
I came to ask...

51
00:02:09.830 --> 00:02:11.040
forgiveness.

52
00:02:11.210 --> 00:02:13.880
[Claire] ♪ Beside the seaside ♪

53
00:02:14.050 --> 00:02:17.170
♪ Oh. I do like to be ♪

54
00:02:17.340 --> 00:02:19.550
♪ Beside the sea ♪

55
00:02:19.720 --> 00:02:22.970
[Fanny]
♪ So just let me be ♪

56
00:02:23.140 --> 00:02:26.020
♪ Beside the seaside ♪

57
00:02:26.180 --> 00:02:28.600
How could you possibly know
that song?

58
00:02:29.020 --> 00:02:31.020
♪ ♪

59
00:02:31.150 --> 00:02:32.900
My mother taught it to me.

60
00:02:33.070 --> 00:02:35.110
I think Faith lived.

61
00:02:36.360 --> 00:02:38.820
I think our daughter lived.
[cries]

62
00:02:38.990 --> 00:02:41.950
♪ ♪

63
00:02:43.200 --> 00:02:45.120
Where the bloody hell is he?

64
00:02:46.330 --> 00:02:47.370
He'll come.

65
00:02:48.290 --> 00:02:50.880
No smuggler worth his salt
would miss the chance

66
00:02:51.040 --> 00:02:53.420
to sell thirty barrels
of good whisky.

67
00:02:53.590 --> 00:02:55.340
Well. I just hope
he doesn't get close enough

68
00:02:55.500 --> 00:02:56.670
to smell the herring.

69
00:02:57.170 --> 00:02:58.630
I willna allow it.

70
00:03:00.220 --> 00:03:01.970
Much as I love the sound
of your voice. Sassenach.

71
00:03:02.140 --> 00:03:04.560
try not to speak
unless spoken to.

72
00:03:04.720 --> 00:03:06.310
[banging on door]

73
00:03:06.720 --> 00:03:07.770
[sighs]

74
00:03:07.890 --> 00:03:10.520
[tense music plays]

75
00:03:10.690 --> 00:03:13.690
♪ ♪

76
00:03:26.240 --> 00:03:29.000
You have exquisite taste.
Mr. Roy.

77
00:03:29.580 --> 00:03:30.960
Aye.

78
00:03:31.120 --> 00:03:33.130
You'll no' have trouble
finding buyers in the north.

79
00:03:33.580 --> 00:03:35.250
Armies there will be thirsty.

80
00:03:35.670 --> 00:03:38.960
You'll easily double
your investment.

81
00:03:39.470 --> 00:03:41.260
[Vasquez] Who gave you my name?

82
00:03:41.430 --> 00:03:44.930
Mrs. Abbott in Philadelphia.

83
00:03:46.720 --> 00:03:49.310
Do you often take
business advice from whores?

84
00:03:49.480 --> 00:03:53.060
[Jamie] Mrs. Abbott tells me
ye're a man to be trusted.

85
00:03:53.600 --> 00:03:56.570
Recalls ye didna have
the money to pay your debts.

86
00:03:57.110 --> 00:03:59.610
and it took ye a wee while.
but. uh.

87
00:04:00.030 --> 00:04:03.610
ye returned with something
much better than coin...

88
00:04:06.910 --> 00:04:10.410
...two lassies
to settle your score.

89
00:04:11.250 --> 00:04:12.370
Sí.

90
00:04:13.250 --> 00:04:14.330
Así es.

91
00:04:15.210 --> 00:04:19.090
Whisky wasn't the only reason
I wanted to meet. Mr. Vasquez.

92
00:04:19.250 --> 00:04:21.130
I wish to expand my business.

93
00:04:21.720 --> 00:04:23.590
Tell me. where do you
find the girls?

94
00:04:23.720 --> 00:04:26.390
It so happens
I found them at sea.

95
00:04:27.220 --> 00:04:30.640
My men and I were looking
for a ship heavy with goods.

96
00:04:30.810 --> 00:04:32.980
But the captain-
Pocock was his name-

97
00:04:33.140 --> 00:04:35.440
was foolish enough
to bring his family--

98
00:04:35.600 --> 00:04:36.940
a wife...

99
00:04:37.820 --> 00:04:39.190
and two daughters.

100
00:04:39.940 --> 00:04:41.490
With my knife
as encouragement.

101
00:04:41.610 --> 00:04:43.360
he was willing to part
with the cargo

102
00:04:43.530 --> 00:04:45.740
but not so willing
to part with the girls.

103
00:04:45.910 --> 00:04:48.030
So I was forced
to slit his throat.

104
00:04:48.200 --> 00:04:50.700
One of the daughters was
still too young to earn.

105
00:04:50.870 --> 00:04:54.160
Even the smallest man
would tear her to pieces.

106
00:04:54.330 --> 00:04:57.130
But with that face
and those golden curls.

107
00:04:57.290 --> 00:04:59.710
I knew she would soon command
a premium--

108
00:04:59.840 --> 00:05:01.460
an assurance for the future.

109
00:05:01.630 --> 00:05:04.050
But her sister
was ripe and ready.

110
00:05:04.220 --> 00:05:06.590
I don't think
she had ever seen a cock

111
00:05:06.720 --> 00:05:09.050
before I stuck her with mine.

112
00:05:09.180 --> 00:05:11.140
That one will have paid
my debts

113
00:05:11.310 --> 00:05:13.520
a hundred times over by now.

114
00:05:13.680 --> 00:05:15.190
But the captain's wife--

115
00:05:15.350 --> 00:05:18.810
ooh. she would have brought
a pretty penny herself.

116
00:05:18.980 --> 00:05:22.780
Beautiful. wild hair.
skin like velvet.

117
00:05:22.940 --> 00:05:25.740
It's a shame I never
had a chance to fuck her.

118
00:05:25.900 --> 00:05:28.910
She turned into a rabid dog
when I touched her daughter.

119
00:05:29.070 --> 00:05:32.910
scratching. biting.
screaming--too much trouble.

120
00:05:33.080 --> 00:05:34.370
I threw her overboard.

121
00:05:34.540 --> 00:05:36.870
Only death would shut her up.

122
00:05:37.040 --> 00:05:39.250
[laughing]

123
00:05:40.460 --> 00:05:42.960
[groaning]

124
00:05:43.090 --> 00:05:45.920
♪ ♪

125
00:05:57.020 --> 00:05:59.400
[panting]

126
00:05:59.560 --> 00:06:01.270
We need to leave. Sassenach.

127
00:06:01.770 --> 00:06:04.740
♪ ♪

128
00:06:07.320 --> 00:06:08.740
I killed him too quickly.

129
00:06:08.910 --> 00:06:11.160
I should have let
that bastard suffer.

130
00:06:11.330 --> 00:06:13.370
I should have made him
feel every ounce of agony

131
00:06:13.540 --> 00:06:15.200
the body can feel.

132
00:06:15.370 --> 00:06:16.710
And even then--

133
00:06:16.870 --> 00:06:18.370
and even then. it wouldn't be
punishment enough.

134
00:06:18.540 --> 00:06:20.580
Aye. well. the devil
will give him his proper due

135
00:06:20.710 --> 00:06:23.050
for what he did
to Jane and Frances

136
00:06:23.420 --> 00:06:24.130
and Faith.

137
00:06:24.300 --> 00:06:25.550
She was alive.

138
00:06:27.470 --> 00:06:29.380
We could have had
a-a life with her.

139
00:06:29.550 --> 00:06:31.260
and he robbed us
of that chance.

140
00:06:31.430 --> 00:06:32.510
[Jamie] He wasn't the only one.

141
00:06:32.680 --> 00:06:34.060
Ye told me ye held our babe

142
00:06:34.220 --> 00:06:35.720
in ye're hands
all those years ago.

143
00:06:35.890 --> 00:06:37.520
that she was stillborn.
already lost to us.

144
00:06:37.680 --> 00:06:40.350
So how did she come to be
married to a sea captain

145
00:06:40.480 --> 00:06:43.320
-wi' two daughters of her own?
-I don't know.

146
00:06:45.730 --> 00:06:47.070
I don't know.

147
00:06:48.820 --> 00:06:51.370
Mother Hildegarde. I mean.
she must have done something

148
00:06:51.490 --> 00:06:52.660
or...

149
00:06:53.740 --> 00:06:55.160
Master Raymond.

150
00:06:56.080 --> 00:06:58.960
He asked for my forgiveness.
but for what?

151
00:07:00.250 --> 00:07:01.790
Somebody lied.

152
00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:05.210
But why?

153
00:07:06.420 --> 00:07:09.840
W-why would they steal
our child from us?

154
00:07:11.930 --> 00:07:14.100
I always imagined
our daughter in heaven.

155
00:07:15.510 --> 00:07:19.230
I mourned an innocent soul
who hadna had a chance at life.

156
00:07:19.980 --> 00:07:21.690
Then to find out she lived

157
00:07:21.810 --> 00:07:24.480
but that her life
was cut short...

158
00:07:25.820 --> 00:07:27.110
A Dhia.

159
00:07:27.280 --> 00:07:30.110
♪ ♪

160
00:07:30.280 --> 00:07:32.450
She was out there. Jamie.

161
00:07:37.660 --> 00:07:39.620
What did her laugh sound like?

162
00:07:42.460 --> 00:07:43.880
Well. did she--

163
00:07:44.840 --> 00:07:48.300
did she smile in her sleep.
like you and Bree?

164
00:07:48.420 --> 00:07:50.260
[crying]

165
00:07:50.880 --> 00:07:53.220
Who helped her when she cried?

166
00:07:55.010 --> 00:07:56.350
Oh. God.

167
00:07:56.510 --> 00:08:00.600
[crying]
What- what if nobody did?

168
00:08:01.690 --> 00:08:03.190
What- what if she went
through her whole life

169
00:08:03.350 --> 00:08:05.900
thinking that nobody
wanted her. when--

170
00:08:06.480 --> 00:08:09.650
when all we wanted more than
anything in the world was her?

171
00:08:12.030 --> 00:08:14.910
[crying]

172
00:08:15.070 --> 00:08:18.040
♪ ♪

173
00:08:21.500 --> 00:08:23.580
You lost your parents
at a young age.

174
00:08:23.750 --> 00:08:25.250
mo nighean donn...

175
00:08:28.550 --> 00:08:33.130
...wandered the world rootless.
but then we found each other.

176
00:08:33.260 --> 00:08:35.510
♪ ♪

177
00:08:35.640 --> 00:08:39.560
I am the true home
of your heart.

178
00:08:42.390 --> 00:08:44.270
Maybe it was the same
for our daughter.

179
00:08:44.440 --> 00:08:46.560
Maybe she wandered. too.

180
00:08:46.980 --> 00:08:48.860
and found her home.

181
00:08:50.030 --> 00:08:50.940
Made a family.

182
00:08:51.110 --> 00:08:54.570
♪ ♪

183
00:08:54.700 --> 00:08:57.240
She was loved. Claire.

184
00:08:59.740 --> 00:09:01.410
I have to believe that.

185
00:09:04.370 --> 00:09:07.210
[Claire crying softly]

186
00:09:07.380 --> 00:09:10.380
♪ ♪

187
00:09:11.800 --> 00:09:14.550
♪ Sing me a song ♪

188
00:09:14.720 --> 00:09:18.260
♪ Of a lass that is gone ♪

189
00:09:18.430 --> 00:09:22.180
♪ Say. could that lass ♪

190
00:09:22.350 --> 00:09:25.690
♪ Be I? ♪

191
00:09:27.520 --> 00:09:29.770
♪ Merry of soul ♪

192
00:09:29.940 --> 00:09:33.780
♪ She sailed on a day ♪

193
00:09:33.900 --> 00:09:37.070
♪ Over the sea ♪

194
00:09:37.240 --> 00:09:41.330
♪ To Skye ♪

195
00:09:41.950 --> 00:09:44.790
♪ Billow and breeze ♪

196
00:09:44.910 --> 00:09:48.000
♪ Islands and seas ♪

197
00:09:48.170 --> 00:09:50.590
♪ Mountains of rain ♪

198
00:09:50.750 --> 00:09:53.760
♪ And sun ♪

199
00:09:53.880 --> 00:09:57.010
♪ All that was good ♪

200
00:09:57.180 --> 00:10:00.050
♪ All that was fair ♪

201
00:10:00.220 --> 00:10:02.760
♪ All that was me ♪

202
00:10:02.930 --> 00:10:07.980
♪ Is gone ♪

203
00:10:09.190 --> 00:10:11.480
♪ Sing me a song ♪

204
00:10:11.650 --> 00:10:14.400
♪ Of a lass that is gone ♪

205
00:10:14.570 --> 00:10:17.110
♪ Say. could that lass ♪

206
00:10:17.280 --> 00:10:20.700
♪ Be I? ♪

207
00:10:20.820 --> 00:10:23.080
♪ Merry of soul ♪

208
00:10:23.240 --> 00:10:26.790
♪ She sailed on a day ♪

209
00:10:26.960 --> 00:10:30.790
♪ Over ♪

210
00:10:30.960 --> 00:10:34.800
♪ The sea ♪

211
00:10:34.960 --> 00:10:41.260
♪ To Skye ♪

212
00:10:44.390 --> 00:10:47.230
[dramatic music plays]

213
00:10:47.390 --> 00:10:50.060
♪ ♪

214
00:10:50.190 --> 00:10:53.400
[typewriter keys clacking]

215
00:11:13.960 --> 00:11:17.010
[seagulls crying]

216
00:11:21.800 --> 00:11:24.850
[distant hoofbeats]

217
00:11:28.310 --> 00:11:31.310
[breathing deeply]

218
00:11:33.860 --> 00:11:35.320
[inhales sharply]

219
00:11:40.950 --> 00:11:42.860
Have you managed
to sleep at all?

220
00:11:43.450 --> 00:11:46.080
[sighs] No.

221
00:11:46.950 --> 00:11:49.370
Not wi' thinkin'
about our Faith...

222
00:11:51.960 --> 00:11:54.250
...and all that
we still dinna ken.

223
00:11:55.210 --> 00:11:58.130
[pensive music plays]

224
00:11:58.260 --> 00:12:01.260
♪ ♪

225
00:12:07.680 --> 00:12:10.600
-I wish Fanny remembered more.
-Ah.

226
00:12:10.770 --> 00:12:13.770
Aye. she couldna have been
more than five years old

227
00:12:13.940 --> 00:12:15.610
when she was sold
to the brothel.

228
00:12:15.770 --> 00:12:17.230
We shouldn't press her.

229
00:12:17.900 --> 00:12:21.070
She's already suffered
more than any child should.

230
00:12:21.820 --> 00:12:23.570
First her parents...

231
00:12:24.950 --> 00:12:25.990
Jane.

232
00:12:26.580 --> 00:12:27.950
D'ye think we should tell her?

233
00:12:29.950 --> 00:12:31.660
That she's our granddaughter?

234
00:12:32.410 --> 00:12:34.330
How can we explain it to her

235
00:12:35.250 --> 00:12:38.090
when we don't know
how it's possible ourselves?

236
00:12:38.800 --> 00:12:40.800
She might not believe us.

237
00:12:41.380 --> 00:12:42.510
And then we'll have broken

238
00:12:42.670 --> 00:12:45.390
whatever trust
she started having in us.

239
00:12:47.550 --> 00:12:51.020
It's no small miracle
that a piece of Faith

240
00:12:51.140 --> 00:12:53.310
came to be in our lives...

241
00:12:54.640 --> 00:12:55.980
her daughter.

242
00:12:57.190 --> 00:12:58.860
Despite all we've lost.

243
00:12:59.860 --> 00:13:02.440
we can thank the Lord
for that blessing.

244
00:13:03.110 --> 00:13:06.240
[footsteps approaching.
child giggles]

245
00:13:06.410 --> 00:13:08.830
-[Jamie] Ah.
-[Claire sighs]

246
00:13:09.280 --> 00:13:11.950
[faint giggling continues]

247
00:13:12.120 --> 00:13:14.870
[clears throat. sighs]

248
00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:18.000
♪ ♪

249
00:13:21.800 --> 00:13:23.010
Aha!

250
00:13:23.170 --> 00:13:24.340
Good morning.
Grand-père. Grand-mère.

251
00:13:24.510 --> 00:13:25.970
Come down for breakfast.

252
00:13:26.130 --> 00:13:28.010
[Marsali] Did I or did I not
tell ye wee heathens

253
00:13:28.180 --> 00:13:29.390
to let your grandparents sleep?

254
00:13:29.550 --> 00:13:31.430
Now. get away
from there before--

255
00:13:31.600 --> 00:13:32.770
Oh.

256
00:13:33.100 --> 00:13:34.350
Yes. good morning to ye both.

257
00:13:34.520 --> 00:13:36.900
There's some coffee
and a wee bit o' parritch

258
00:13:37.020 --> 00:13:38.230
downstairs when ye're ready.

259
00:13:38.610 --> 00:13:40.070
Sounds wonderful.

260
00:13:40.190 --> 00:13:41.360
Thank you. Marsali.

261
00:13:41.530 --> 00:13:42.690
Aye. and since ye're up.

262
00:13:42.860 --> 00:13:44.570
I wouldn't mind a hand
with the press.

263
00:13:44.740 --> 00:13:46.240
We'll be down shortly.
mon fils.

264
00:13:46.400 --> 00:13:48.740
I'm. uh. eager to see
this workshop of yours.

265
00:13:48.910 --> 00:13:51.870
♪ ♪

266
00:13:53.330 --> 00:13:54.080
[door closes]

267
00:13:54.250 --> 00:13:55.960
-Oh.
-Hmm.

268
00:13:56.120 --> 00:13:59.130
♪ ♪

269
00:14:04.170 --> 00:14:08.130
We were so newly arrived when
the British took over the city.

270
00:14:08.300 --> 00:14:11.010
we had not yet begun
printing the newspaper.

271
00:14:12.390 --> 00:14:16.890
Now I'm careful to be perfectly
impartial in its pages.

272
00:14:17.060 --> 00:14:19.900
if not a bit more complimentary
to the British Army

273
00:14:20.060 --> 00:14:20.900
than they deserve.

274
00:14:21.060 --> 00:14:22.980
[Jamie] Ah. wise choice...

275
00:14:25.190 --> 00:14:26.610
Ah. [chuckles]

276
00:14:26.740 --> 00:14:29.530
...as they may question
the loyalty of a Frenchman.

277
00:14:29.700 --> 00:14:31.240
Indeed.

278
00:14:31.410 --> 00:14:33.240
It also helps that it was
a regiment of Highlanders

279
00:14:33.410 --> 00:14:35.250
who captured Savannah
for the British.

280
00:14:35.410 --> 00:14:37.460
And I happened to have
a Scottish wife...

281
00:14:38.540 --> 00:14:41.500
and the name Fraser
above the door.

282
00:14:43.210 --> 00:14:48.220
For that. I'm forgiven
a multitude of sins.

283
00:14:53.810 --> 00:14:56.310
[knocks on wall]

284
00:15:00.480 --> 00:15:02.520
[knocks on wall]

285
00:15:05.730 --> 00:15:06.860
[hollow knocking]

286
00:15:07.030 --> 00:15:08.990
[soft tense music plays]

287
00:15:09.150 --> 00:15:11.950
[thumping]

288
00:15:12.120 --> 00:15:15.080
♪ ♪

289
00:15:17.790 --> 00:15:20.210
But the British
dinna forgive sedition.

290
00:15:20.370 --> 00:15:22.540
Well. I better not
get caught. then.

291
00:15:25.050 --> 00:15:26.130
Don't worry.

292
00:15:26.590 --> 00:15:28.920
I'm doing everything
you taught me.

293
00:15:29.090 --> 00:15:30.760
Difference is.
you have a family now.

294
00:15:30.930 --> 00:15:32.800
Oui. You had a family then.

295
00:15:32.970 --> 00:15:34.390
And they were safe
in the Highlands.

296
00:15:34.550 --> 00:15:37.350
not wi' me in Edinburgh.
There wasna a war then.

297
00:15:37.470 --> 00:15:39.850
Which is why this work
is even more vital

298
00:15:40.020 --> 00:15:41.190
than what we did before.

299
00:15:41.350 --> 00:15:43.190
Which is why it's also
more dangerous.

300
00:15:43.360 --> 00:15:44.650
In these times.

301
00:15:44.810 --> 00:15:46.690
there's little one can do
that isn't dangerous.

302
00:15:48.650 --> 00:15:50.240
If I'm going to be killed
for something.

303
00:15:50.400 --> 00:15:53.320
I should like it to be
something that matters.

304
00:15:54.820 --> 00:15:57.330
[speaking French]

305
00:15:59.620 --> 00:16:01.000
[sighs sharply]

306
00:16:01.160 --> 00:16:04.130
♪ ♪

307
00:16:08.300 --> 00:16:10.880
Just promise me
ye'll be careful.

308
00:16:13.300 --> 00:16:14.510
Toujours.

309
00:16:14.680 --> 00:16:17.180
♪ ♪

310
00:16:17.350 --> 00:16:18.430
[indistinct chatter]

311
00:16:18.600 --> 00:16:21.180
[chuckling]

312
00:16:21.350 --> 00:16:23.440
Why didn't Uncle Ian
come with you. Grand-pére?

313
00:16:23.600 --> 00:16:26.020
Ah. he very much wanted
to see you. a bhalaich.

314
00:16:26.190 --> 00:16:27.980
but your new auntie Rachel
is with child.

315
00:16:28.110 --> 00:16:30.820
so he was eager to get her
settled back on the Ridge.

316
00:16:30.990 --> 00:16:32.610
I canna fault him for that.

317
00:16:32.780 --> 00:16:35.320
given the luck he's had
with bairns.

318
00:16:35.870 --> 00:16:37.200
Cookies for breakfast!

319
00:16:37.370 --> 00:16:39.120
[all cheering]

320
00:16:39.290 --> 00:16:41.120
Well. what are grannies for?
Mmm.

321
00:16:41.250 --> 00:16:42.410
[grunting]

322
00:16:42.580 --> 00:16:45.420
-Now. there you go.
-Ooh. Uh...

323
00:16:45.540 --> 00:16:48.210
-three dozen all for me.
-Hey!

324
00:16:48.380 --> 00:16:49.500
How do you do that?

325
00:16:49.670 --> 00:16:51.260
Oh. it's not difficult.
Sassenach.

326
00:16:51.420 --> 00:16:53.170
It's easier than
counting goats and sheep.

327
00:16:53.340 --> 00:16:55.680
After all. cookies
dinna have legs. huh. hmm?

328
00:16:55.800 --> 00:16:57.260
-Legs?
-Aye.

329
00:16:57.430 --> 00:16:59.100
Ah. to know how many
goats ye have.

330
00:16:59.220 --> 00:17:01.810
ye must count all the legs
and divide by four.

331
00:17:01.980 --> 00:17:03.730
[chuckling]

332
00:17:03.890 --> 00:17:05.270
Maybe Fanny would be so kind

333
00:17:05.440 --> 00:17:07.060
as to help ye all count out
the morning deliveries

334
00:17:07.190 --> 00:17:08.400
before the news
goes stale. hmm?

335
00:17:08.520 --> 00:17:09.570
Come on. lad.

336
00:17:09.730 --> 00:17:12.280
[all chuckling]

337
00:17:12.400 --> 00:17:15.240
-Thanks. Granny.
-Mwah. You're welcome.

338
00:17:15.360 --> 00:17:16.990
[Jamie] Oh. Aye. help yourself.

339
00:17:17.160 --> 00:17:19.490
[laughter]

340
00:17:21.620 --> 00:17:23.750
Henri-Christian
seems to be thriving.

341
00:17:23.910 --> 00:17:24.710
Aye.

342
00:17:25.040 --> 00:17:27.040
He's our joy. our wee lad.

343
00:17:27.210 --> 00:17:29.040
Fanny's a sweet lass.

344
00:17:29.460 --> 00:17:30.880
[sighs] And bright. too.

345
00:17:31.050 --> 00:17:32.510
She seems remarkably unspoiled

346
00:17:32.670 --> 00:17:34.130
for one who grew up
in a brothel.

347
00:17:34.260 --> 00:17:37.220
Aye. her sister protected
her innocence and virtue.

348
00:17:37.390 --> 00:17:38.600
so far as she could.

349
00:17:38.760 --> 00:17:41.100
Still. it cannot be easy
for her.

350
00:17:41.260 --> 00:17:43.310
A brothel is not
an ideal place for a child.

351
00:17:43.430 --> 00:17:46.140
but it is home if that's
the only home she's known.

352
00:17:46.730 --> 00:17:49.310
To lose that
and her sister as well...

353
00:17:50.230 --> 00:17:52.320
That's why we canna stay
much longer.

354
00:17:52.440 --> 00:17:55.030
I made a promise
to Frances and to Claire.

355
00:17:55.200 --> 00:17:56.150
[chuckles]

356
00:17:56.320 --> 00:17:57.950
'Tis time to go home.

357
00:17:58.820 --> 00:18:00.950
But we will miss
you all terribly.

358
00:18:01.660 --> 00:18:03.160
We'll miss you. too.

359
00:18:03.910 --> 00:18:06.830
But it won't be goodbye.
only au revoir.

360
00:18:06.960 --> 00:18:09.040
[chuckles]

361
00:18:10.920 --> 00:18:13.460
[majestic music plays]

362
00:18:13.630 --> 00:18:16.590
♪ ♪

363
00:18:18.340 --> 00:18:19.590
[Fanny] Are we nearly there?

364
00:18:19.720 --> 00:18:21.510
[gasps] When will we get
to Fraser's Ridge?

365
00:18:21.680 --> 00:18:24.310
[Jamie] We've been on
the Ridge the past two days.

366
00:18:24.470 --> 00:18:27.020
You mean all of this is yours?

367
00:18:27.140 --> 00:18:28.690
Aye. a leannain.

368
00:18:28.850 --> 00:18:31.360
'Tis ours. as far as
ye're eyes can see.

369
00:18:31.520 --> 00:18:32.820
[Claire] This is our home.

370
00:18:34.780 --> 00:18:36.190
Your home.

371
00:18:36.360 --> 00:18:39.360
♪ ♪

372
00:18:41.280 --> 00:18:43.330
[baby crying]

373
00:18:43.490 --> 00:18:45.950
[Lord John]
You woke the baby. damn you!

374
00:18:46.120 --> 00:18:47.500
[grunts]

375
00:18:48.250 --> 00:18:49.870
[Lt. Graves] This man was taken
into our custody

376
00:18:50.040 --> 00:18:52.880
during an altercation with a
band of rebels outside of town.

377
00:18:53.040 --> 00:18:54.840
He claims to be
the ninth Earl of Ellesmere

378
00:18:54.960 --> 00:18:56.800
and a former soldier
in His Majesty's Army.

379
00:18:56.970 --> 00:18:58.010
Captain.

380
00:18:58.170 --> 00:19:00.130
I was a captain
in His Majesty's Army

381
00:19:00.300 --> 00:19:01.590
before I resigned
my commission.

382
00:19:01.760 --> 00:19:03.390
[Graves]
We believe him to be a spy.

383
00:19:03.560 --> 00:19:06.520
He assured us you could offer
some clarity on the matter.

384
00:19:06.680 --> 00:19:08.310
Yes.
I understand the confusion.

385
00:19:08.480 --> 00:19:11.560
given as His Lordship currently
appears more like a highwayman

386
00:19:11.730 --> 00:19:13.020
than an earl.

387
00:19:14.440 --> 00:19:17.820
But I assure you. he is.
in fact. who he says he is.

388
00:19:17.940 --> 00:19:19.950
He poses no threat
to our country...

389
00:19:20.070 --> 00:19:20.740
-[baby fusses]
-Shh.

390
00:19:20.910 --> 00:19:22.280
...or our cause.

391
00:19:22.910 --> 00:19:24.080
Then I am satisfied.

392
00:19:24.660 --> 00:19:26.120
Apologies for the intrusion.
My Lord.

393
00:19:26.290 --> 00:19:27.330
Good day to you.

394
00:19:27.500 --> 00:19:30.500
♪ ♪

395
00:19:32.380 --> 00:19:34.540
-Little fiend is teething.
-[door opens]

396
00:19:34.710 --> 00:19:37.630
And the lack of sleep
won't improve his temper.

397
00:19:37.800 --> 00:19:39.340
-Yours?
-[door closes]

398
00:19:39.510 --> 00:19:40.840
Surely. you jest.

399
00:19:41.010 --> 00:19:42.180
[laughs]

400
00:19:42.340 --> 00:19:46.720
Allow me to introduce
Trevor Wattiswade Grey.

401
00:19:46.890 --> 00:19:48.560
your cousin Benjamin's son.

402
00:19:48.730 --> 00:19:51.600
[gagging. retching]

403
00:19:51.770 --> 00:19:54.520
[spits. coughing]

404
00:20:03.320 --> 00:20:04.620
[Fanny]
This is where you lived?

405
00:20:04.780 --> 00:20:06.030
[chuckles]

406
00:20:06.200 --> 00:20:08.950
Ah. it's so overgrown now.

407
00:20:09.830 --> 00:20:11.660
I can hardly believe
there was a fire here

408
00:20:11.830 --> 00:20:13.710
if I hadn't seen it myself.

409
00:20:16.090 --> 00:20:18.920
The earth takes
everything back in the end.

410
00:20:20.590 --> 00:20:23.840
[carriage approaching]

411
00:20:23.970 --> 00:20:25.430
Ah!

412
00:20:25.600 --> 00:20:27.970
-Ian!
-[Jamie chuckles]

413
00:20:28.890 --> 00:20:29.970
A bhalaich!

414
00:20:30.770 --> 00:20:32.640
-Auntie. Uncle.
-[Jamie] A bhalaich.

415
00:20:32.810 --> 00:20:34.810
[chuckling]

416
00:20:38.520 --> 00:20:40.530
And you remember Frances.
of course.

417
00:20:40.690 --> 00:20:43.400
Aye. Welcome to Fraser's Ridge.

418
00:20:44.160 --> 00:20:45.660
And Rachel? Has the baby...?

419
00:20:45.780 --> 00:20:47.280
The bairn hasna come yet.

420
00:20:47.450 --> 00:20:49.490
Rachel will be most pleased
to see ye.

421
00:20:49.660 --> 00:20:53.080
But first. will ye lend me
a hand with this?

422
00:20:53.250 --> 00:20:54.120
Aye.

423
00:20:54.580 --> 00:20:57.460
♪ ♪

424
00:20:57.590 --> 00:20:59.710
What have you done
to the corncrib. lad?

425
00:21:00.510 --> 00:21:02.590
And where are the stables?

426
00:21:02.720 --> 00:21:04.590
Ah. Follow me.

427
00:21:04.760 --> 00:21:05.760
I've something to show you.

428
00:21:05.930 --> 00:21:09.510
♪ ♪

429
00:21:16.310 --> 00:21:17.980
What in God's name
happened to you?

430
00:21:18.150 --> 00:21:20.860
A rumor reached me
that a turncoat captain

431
00:21:20.980 --> 00:21:22.240
may have been fighting
with the rebels

432
00:21:22.650 --> 00:21:24.240
when our troops
captured the city.

433
00:21:24.400 --> 00:21:27.200
And you thought that captain
was Ezekiel Richardson?

434
00:21:27.370 --> 00:21:28.620
I came to find out.

435
00:21:29.530 --> 00:21:31.330
None of the rebels
would speak to me

436
00:21:31.830 --> 00:21:34.540
until I suggested ale
and a game of brag.

437
00:21:36.170 --> 00:21:38.330
And did you manage
to learn the whereabouts

438
00:21:38.500 --> 00:21:40.550
of that traitorous bastard?

439
00:21:41.000 --> 00:21:42.090
I'm sorry.

440
00:21:42.260 --> 00:21:44.170
Did you say that was
my cousin's baby?

441
00:21:45.430 --> 00:21:47.260
Ben's got a baby?

442
00:21:47.390 --> 00:21:48.590
And a wife.

443
00:21:48.760 --> 00:21:50.600
I had no idea.
but I'm glad he's here.

444
00:21:50.760 --> 00:21:52.100
I'll be most pleased
to see him.

445
00:21:52.220 --> 00:21:54.100
H-has his regiment
been transferred?

446
00:21:54.600 --> 00:21:55.730
He's. um...

447
00:21:57.150 --> 00:21:58.270
not here.

448
00:21:59.360 --> 00:22:00.610
William. I am...

449
00:22:02.980 --> 00:22:05.400
...I'm very sorry
to tell you that...

450
00:22:06.240 --> 00:22:07.410
Ben is dead.

451
00:22:09.910 --> 00:22:12.120
[breathing shakily]

452
00:22:12.290 --> 00:22:13.910
No. that's impossible.

453
00:22:15.000 --> 00:22:17.750
He was taken prisoner
while out with a raiding party

454
00:22:18.790 --> 00:22:21.170
and held by rebels
at Middlebrook encampment

455
00:22:21.340 --> 00:22:22.500
in New Jersey.

456
00:22:22.840 --> 00:22:24.590
[somber music plays]

457
00:22:24.710 --> 00:22:26.220
There was...

458
00:22:27.340 --> 00:22:29.340
an outbreak of jail fever.

459
00:22:29.720 --> 00:22:32.720
♪ ♪

460
00:22:36.100 --> 00:22:37.480
I was...

461
00:22:38.560 --> 00:22:40.900
terribly saddened
to hear the news...

462
00:22:42.690 --> 00:22:44.480
...as I knew you would be. too.

463
00:22:46.740 --> 00:22:48.860
I know how much
you looked up to him.

464
00:22:51.200 --> 00:22:53.830
Who was the commander
of this raiding party?

465
00:22:56.040 --> 00:22:57.620
How was Ben captured?

466
00:22:58.290 --> 00:23:00.040
Were any of his comrades
taken with him?

467
00:23:00.210 --> 00:23:03.130
♪ ♪

468
00:23:09.970 --> 00:23:12.010
I've given you
all the information I have.

469
00:23:13.300 --> 00:23:14.720
Does Uncle Hal know?

470
00:23:15.890 --> 00:23:17.060
Does Henry?

471
00:23:18.850 --> 00:23:19.890
Not yet.

472
00:23:22.230 --> 00:23:25.820
I've drafted a letter
to my brother

473
00:23:25.980 --> 00:23:27.320
half a dozen times.

474
00:23:28.030 --> 00:23:29.490
But I'm afraid
once he finds out

475
00:23:29.650 --> 00:23:33.070
that his eldest and favorite
son is dead. then...

476
00:23:34.080 --> 00:23:36.990
he will die
of heartbreak. and...

477
00:23:38.410 --> 00:23:40.290
I do not think
I could bear that.

478
00:23:41.540 --> 00:23:42.670
And the child?

479
00:23:45.630 --> 00:23:48.010
Not long
after I'd received news

480
00:23:48.170 --> 00:23:50.340
of Benjamin's death.

481
00:23:51.090 --> 00:23:54.350
a young lady appeared
on my doorstep with her baby.

482
00:23:55.560 --> 00:23:59.020
claiming she was. um.
Benjamin's widow.

483
00:23:59.520 --> 00:24:03.150
Seems the young Lady Grey

484
00:24:03.730 --> 00:24:05.980
had fallen
into difficult circumstances.

485
00:24:06.150 --> 00:24:08.400
owing to her husband's absence.

486
00:24:10.190 --> 00:24:11.780
And so. um...

487
00:24:12.530 --> 00:24:14.280
I invited her to stay.

488
00:24:14.450 --> 00:24:15.580
Wait.

489
00:24:16.200 --> 00:24:17.990
You'd never heard of this wife

490
00:24:18.450 --> 00:24:21.080
until after you received word
of Ben's death?

491
00:24:23.170 --> 00:24:25.170
[scoffs]
No. I-I don't believe it.

492
00:24:25.290 --> 00:24:28.380
If-if Ben were married.
he would have told me.

493
00:24:29.760 --> 00:24:31.880
When is the last time
you received a letter from Ben?

494
00:24:32.050 --> 00:24:34.050
I'll admit. I allowed
our correspondence to lapse

495
00:24:34.220 --> 00:24:35.260
after...

496
00:24:36.300 --> 00:24:38.680
everything that happened
last year. but...

497
00:24:40.060 --> 00:24:42.100
but he would have told
his brother.

498
00:24:42.230 --> 00:24:44.730
And Henry never
mentioned anything.

499
00:24:45.650 --> 00:24:48.440
The young lady arrived
with a bundle of love letters.

500
00:24:49.190 --> 00:24:51.110
all sealed
with Benjamin's signet ring.

501
00:24:51.240 --> 00:24:53.360
And the boy's name. Wattiswade.

502
00:24:53.530 --> 00:24:55.910
is a family name
not commonly known.

503
00:24:56.570 --> 00:24:58.080
I believe her claim.

504
00:24:58.200 --> 00:25:00.240
Any charlatan hoping to profit
off our family's grief

505
00:25:00.410 --> 00:25:01.580
could falsify love letters.

506
00:25:01.750 --> 00:25:03.580
Clearly. you've been hoodwinked
by some--

507
00:25:03.750 --> 00:25:04.710
some damn woman.

508
00:25:04.830 --> 00:25:06.880
Some damn woman. am I?

509
00:25:07.210 --> 00:25:09.880
[tense music plays]

510
00:25:10.050 --> 00:25:12.170
♪ ♪

511
00:25:12.340 --> 00:25:16.220
William. may I present
Amaranthus. Viscountess Grey.

512
00:25:17.010 --> 00:25:18.300
Benjamin's widow.

513
00:25:20.140 --> 00:25:22.310
Ben did speak
of a Cousin William.

514
00:25:23.600 --> 00:25:26.060
though he neglected
to mention said cousin

515
00:25:26.230 --> 00:25:28.610
was a drunkard and a fool.

516
00:25:29.940 --> 00:25:31.400
Good day. Uncle John.

517
00:25:32.530 --> 00:25:34.990
♪ ♪

518
00:25:35.110 --> 00:25:36.200
[sighs]

519
00:25:36.360 --> 00:25:39.160
[light music plays]

520
00:25:39.330 --> 00:25:42.290
♪ ♪

521
00:26:01.600 --> 00:26:04.770
Welcome home. [chuckles]

522
00:26:04.930 --> 00:26:06.810
What have ye done. lad?
What is this?

523
00:26:07.270 --> 00:26:08.310
Built yer house for ye.

524
00:26:08.480 --> 00:26:10.820
-Our house?
-[Young Ian] Aye.

525
00:26:10.980 --> 00:26:12.690
I took the plans ye made
before you left.

526
00:26:12.860 --> 00:26:13.990
Called everyone together--

527
00:26:14.150 --> 00:26:16.150
the Beardsleys.
the-the Lindsays.

528
00:26:16.320 --> 00:26:17.660
and some of yer
other Ardsmuir men.

529
00:26:17.780 --> 00:26:19.200
Tore down the stables

530
00:26:19.370 --> 00:26:21.030
and used that lumber
for the start.

531
00:26:22.120 --> 00:26:23.660
And then when folk got word
of what we were about.

532
00:26:23.830 --> 00:26:26.910
they'd come by with wood or
furnishings they could spare.

533
00:26:27.080 --> 00:26:28.290
even jes' to lend a hand.

534
00:26:28.460 --> 00:26:29.750
-[Jamie] A Dhia.
-[Young Ian chuckles]

535
00:26:29.920 --> 00:26:33.170
[sighs]
Ian. oh. it's beautiful.

536
00:26:33.340 --> 00:26:34.590
[Young Ian]
Dinna worry. Auntie.

537
00:26:34.760 --> 00:26:36.590
I've staked out
a wee garden for ye.

538
00:26:39.840 --> 00:26:41.430
[Claire] Oh.

539
00:26:42.760 --> 00:26:44.930
I thought I heard voices.

540
00:26:45.520 --> 00:26:46.480
[Claire] Rachel.

541
00:26:46.640 --> 00:26:48.770
[gasps] Look at you.

542
00:26:48.940 --> 00:26:50.190
You're glowing.

543
00:26:50.350 --> 00:26:52.020
-How are you?
-I'm well.

544
00:26:52.190 --> 00:26:54.230
Now. would you like
to see thy house?

545
00:26:54.400 --> 00:26:56.650
Iain Oig. Moran taing dhut.

546
00:26:56.820 --> 00:26:58.450
You're very welcome. Uncle.

547
00:26:58.820 --> 00:27:01.780
♪ ♪

548
00:27:03.410 --> 00:27:04.910
[door opens]

549
00:27:05.410 --> 00:27:08.370
♪ ♪

550
00:27:09.670 --> 00:27:11.380
Well? What do you think?

551
00:27:11.540 --> 00:27:12.630
[chuckles]

552
00:27:12.790 --> 00:27:14.670
[Claire gasps. chuckles]

553
00:27:14.840 --> 00:27:16.800
-[Young Ian chuckles]
-[Claire] Wow. Ian.

554
00:27:16.960 --> 00:27:18.220
[Rachel chuckles]

555
00:27:18.380 --> 00:27:20.630
-[Jamie] Ah.
-[Young Ian] It's not just me.

556
00:27:20.760 --> 00:27:22.720
[chuckles] A lot of hands.

557
00:27:22.890 --> 00:27:26.470
Just like I imagined.
These are from the stables.

558
00:27:26.600 --> 00:27:27.890
[Claire] Look at this view.

559
00:27:28.060 --> 00:27:29.020
[Young Ian]
Aye. it's a beautiful spot.

560
00:27:29.190 --> 00:27:30.770
[Claire] Oh. it's fantastic.

561
00:27:30.940 --> 00:27:32.360
Kitchen.

562
00:27:33.270 --> 00:27:36.280
♪ ♪

563
00:27:39.400 --> 00:27:42.820
Ken ye need plenty of light
for yer surgeries.

564
00:27:43.370 --> 00:27:46.580
so I made the south-facing
windows nice and big.

565
00:27:48.950 --> 00:27:50.710
And I built the table from
memory.

566
00:27:50.870 --> 00:27:52.420
Hope it's the proper height.

567
00:27:53.710 --> 00:27:55.250
Is it to thy liking. Claire?

568
00:27:55.800 --> 00:27:57.550
I don't know what to say.

569
00:27:57.670 --> 00:27:59.510
[Rachel and Young Ian chuckle]

570
00:27:59.670 --> 00:28:02.260
♪ ♪

571
00:28:02.390 --> 00:28:04.720
[Claire] Where did you get
all these things?

572
00:28:04.890 --> 00:28:08.640
Oh. some I found when we passed
through Wilmington.

573
00:28:08.810 --> 00:28:11.310
The rest is from
the new trading post--

574
00:28:11.480 --> 00:28:14.190
Hiram Crombie's. running down
by the meeting house.

575
00:28:19.320 --> 00:28:23.610
Oh. Ian. Rachel. this is...

576
00:28:24.160 --> 00:28:26.120
-this is so thoughtful.
-[Young Ian chuckles]

577
00:28:26.280 --> 00:28:28.080
I'm so overwhelmed.

578
00:28:28.240 --> 00:28:30.620
Well. I'd be lying if I said
I wasna a wee bit selfish

579
00:28:30.790 --> 00:28:32.120
in putting this together.

580
00:28:32.290 --> 00:28:36.290
seeing as I have yer first
two patients right here.

581
00:28:37.040 --> 00:28:38.840
Well. I promise I will take

582
00:28:39.000 --> 00:28:41.340
very. very good care
of them both.

583
00:28:41.510 --> 00:28:43.720
♪ ♪

584
00:28:43.880 --> 00:28:46.100
Ah. here are the plans.

585
00:28:48.930 --> 00:28:50.140
Frances...

586
00:28:51.600 --> 00:28:52.980
have a look upstairs.

587
00:28:53.140 --> 00:28:56.150
[grunting]

588
00:29:08.330 --> 00:29:10.450
What do ye think
of this room. Frances?

589
00:29:11.040 --> 00:29:12.660
It's nice. Mr. Fraser.

590
00:29:13.210 --> 00:29:16.580
So. um. ye wouldna
be disappointed

591
00:29:16.750 --> 00:29:20.630
if I were to tell ye I was
thinking it should be yours?

592
00:29:20.750 --> 00:29:21.920
[chuckles]

593
00:29:22.090 --> 00:29:24.470
I could build you an. uh--

594
00:29:24.630 --> 00:29:27.180
an armoire over here
for your clothes

595
00:29:27.340 --> 00:29:31.350
and a-a wee chair to sit
and read...

596
00:29:32.100 --> 00:29:33.270
if you like.

597
00:29:34.600 --> 00:29:37.940
You mean a whole room
of my own?

598
00:29:39.320 --> 00:29:40.770
If it suits ye.

599
00:29:42.780 --> 00:29:44.240
It suits me well.

600
00:29:45.700 --> 00:29:49.030
[distant bird calling.
insects chirping]

601
00:30:00.210 --> 00:30:01.420
[door closes]

602
00:30:10.470 --> 00:30:13.270
The shape of you
in the moonlight. Sassenach...

603
00:30:14.640 --> 00:30:17.100
you look just as ye did

604
00:30:17.480 --> 00:30:19.360
the night we made our Faith.

605
00:30:22.900 --> 00:30:24.990
You know when
she was conceived?

606
00:30:25.110 --> 00:30:26.900
-Aye.
-I don't even know that.

607
00:30:27.070 --> 00:30:30.240
Ah. well. I may be wrong.
of course. but...

608
00:30:30.370 --> 00:30:31.450
[Claire] Hmm.

609
00:30:31.620 --> 00:30:34.370
...I always thought
it was the night

610
00:30:34.540 --> 00:30:36.540
ye first told me ye loved me...

611
00:30:38.250 --> 00:30:41.630
...in the Laird's chamber.
Lallybroch.

612
00:30:43.500 --> 00:30:45.340
Ye were standing
near the window.

613
00:30:46.340 --> 00:30:49.470
The moon was streaming in
just so.

614
00:30:50.140 --> 00:30:51.600
as I came to ye.

615
00:30:52.010 --> 00:30:54.890
[sentimental music plays]

616
00:30:55.020 --> 00:30:56.890
♪ ♪

617
00:30:57.060 --> 00:30:58.310
[Claire] Mm.

618
00:30:58.850 --> 00:31:00.520
You told me...

619
00:31:01.560 --> 00:31:04.480
that you wanted me from
the first time you ever saw me.

620
00:31:04.610 --> 00:31:05.400
[Jamie] Mm.

621
00:31:06.150 --> 00:31:09.950
Had something to do
with my hard head...

622
00:31:10.110 --> 00:31:11.530
-Mm-hmm.
-...and my round arse.

623
00:31:11.700 --> 00:31:14.080
Hmm. so you do recall
the occasion.

624
00:31:14.240 --> 00:31:15.910
-Hmm?
-[both chuckle]

625
00:31:16.080 --> 00:31:19.000
♪ ♪

626
00:31:29.630 --> 00:31:33.470
How do you know that was
the night Faith was conceived?

627
00:31:33.600 --> 00:31:34.640
I wanted ye.

628
00:31:36.060 --> 00:31:37.350
I had to have ye.

629
00:31:38.890 --> 00:31:40.730
And once I was inside ye.

630
00:31:41.730 --> 00:31:45.480
I'd have been content if that
was the last thing I ever felt.

631
00:31:47.400 --> 00:31:48.900
[sighs]

632
00:31:49.070 --> 00:31:50.570
Then we started...

633
00:31:51.990 --> 00:31:56.080
and I kent a piece of myself
would be inside you forever...

634
00:32:02.420 --> 00:32:05.040
...'cause I was giving you
a child.

635
00:32:05.210 --> 00:32:08.170
♪ ♪

636
00:32:14.090 --> 00:32:17.010
[light music plays]

637
00:32:17.180 --> 00:32:19.980
♪ ♪

638
00:32:20.140 --> 00:32:23.150
[indistinct chatter]

639
00:32:25.610 --> 00:32:27.480
[bird squawks]

640
00:32:27.650 --> 00:32:30.690
♪ ♪

641
00:32:35.870 --> 00:32:38.950
When Ian told me
Crombie had a trading post.

642
00:32:39.450 --> 00:32:41.290
I didn't expect all this.

643
00:32:41.620 --> 00:32:44.460
♪ ♪

644
00:32:44.630 --> 00:32:47.340
[distant dog barking]

645
00:32:52.340 --> 00:32:54.300
[Amy] Mr. and Mrs. Fraser.

646
00:32:54.760 --> 00:32:55.640
Boys.

647
00:32:56.260 --> 00:32:58.180
We'd just heard word
of your return.

648
00:32:58.350 --> 00:32:59.260
Amy.

649
00:32:59.720 --> 00:33:02.270
Oh. it's so good
to see you again.

650
00:33:02.810 --> 00:33:05.560
Mrs. McCallum
and wee Aidan and Orrie.

651
00:33:05.730 --> 00:33:07.190
Not so wee anymore. eh. lads?

652
00:33:07.360 --> 00:33:08.690
[chuckles] Thank you.

653
00:33:08.860 --> 00:33:11.860
And. uh. my name is not
McCallum anymore either.

654
00:33:12.530 --> 00:33:14.740
It's Lindsay now. [laughs]

655
00:33:14.910 --> 00:33:15.990
Evan!

656
00:33:16.990 --> 00:33:17.870
Mac Dubh!

657
00:33:18.030 --> 00:33:18.780
Evan.

658
00:33:19.490 --> 00:33:21.660
Congratulations
on your new family.

659
00:33:21.830 --> 00:33:23.040
Dinna ken you had it in ye.

660
00:33:23.210 --> 00:33:25.290
I'm over the moon.
Couldna be happier.

661
00:33:26.210 --> 00:33:28.670
And thank you so much for
all your help with the house.

662
00:33:28.840 --> 00:33:30.000
No need.

663
00:33:30.170 --> 00:33:31.090
The both of ye would have done
the same thing

664
00:33:31.260 --> 00:33:32.550
for any one of us.

665
00:33:32.720 --> 00:33:35.010
Beam by beam.
it was like a little prayer.

666
00:33:35.130 --> 00:33:36.340
calling you home.

667
00:33:37.550 --> 00:33:41.060
Either my eyes deceive me
or the Frasers have come back.

668
00:33:41.930 --> 00:33:43.310
I bid ye both welcome.

669
00:33:44.230 --> 00:33:46.270
It's quite an establishment
you have here. Mr. Crombie.

670
00:33:46.440 --> 00:33:48.860
[chuckles]
Well. the Bible instructs us

671
00:33:48.980 --> 00:33:51.280
to use our gifts to serve
one another as stewards

672
00:33:51.400 --> 00:33:52.820
of the grace of God.

673
00:33:53.740 --> 00:33:55.780
I've discovered that I'm quite
gifted in procuring things

674
00:33:55.900 --> 00:33:59.160
that people need.
like this fabric.

675
00:33:59.740 --> 00:34:01.330
Will it do for ye.
Mrs. Lindsay?

676
00:34:01.740 --> 00:34:03.200
That'll do nicely. thank ye.

677
00:34:03.950 --> 00:34:07.580
May I acquaint you
with our enterprise?

678
00:34:08.960 --> 00:34:10.670
So good to see you again.

679
00:34:14.010 --> 00:34:17.050
[indistinct chatter]

680
00:34:18.930 --> 00:34:20.680
[Hiram]
We have many fine fabrics.

681
00:34:20.850 --> 00:34:22.640
and these just arrived.

682
00:34:22.810 --> 00:34:26.640
And here ye'll find the tools
of yer trade. Mrs. Fraser.

683
00:34:28.440 --> 00:34:29.440
Oh.

684
00:34:30.020 --> 00:34:32.780
It'll be so nice not to have
to send to Woolam's Creek

685
00:34:32.900 --> 00:34:33.900
for some of these.

686
00:34:34.780 --> 00:34:37.490
You don't happen to have any
Jesuit bark hidden somewhere?

687
00:34:37.650 --> 00:34:40.910
That's another name
for cinchona bark. is it not?

688
00:34:41.030 --> 00:34:42.370
[chuckles softly] It is.

689
00:34:42.530 --> 00:34:43.790
Mrs. Beardsley was asking

690
00:34:43.950 --> 00:34:45.290
for the very same thing
just yesterday.

691
00:34:45.450 --> 00:34:47.370
We shall have to procure some.
Mr. Crombie.

692
00:34:47.540 --> 00:34:51.000
I-I was actually looking for it
to make a tonic for her.

693
00:34:51.170 --> 00:34:52.290
Ah.

694
00:34:52.420 --> 00:34:53.710
I dinna believe
we have the pleasure

695
00:34:53.840 --> 00:34:55.340
-of your acquaintance. sir.
-Oh. forgive me.

696
00:34:56.010 --> 00:34:58.260
This is
Captain Charles Cunningham.

697
00:34:58.430 --> 00:35:00.470
He is my partner
in this endeavor.

698
00:35:01.050 --> 00:35:05.350
Captain. these are the Frasers.
newly returned.

699
00:35:05.520 --> 00:35:07.310
General and Mrs. Fraser.

700
00:35:07.430 --> 00:35:09.770
I'm so pleased
to finally meet you.

701
00:35:10.150 --> 00:35:11.400
It's been rather strange

702
00:35:11.560 --> 00:35:12.770
for my mother and I to live
on this land.

703
00:35:12.940 --> 00:35:14.400
never having met its owners.

704
00:35:14.570 --> 00:35:16.070
Uh. partners. ye say?

705
00:35:16.240 --> 00:35:17.990
When I arrived
on Fraser's Ridge.

706
00:35:18.150 --> 00:35:21.070
it seemed a bit of commerce
might do some good.

707
00:35:21.530 --> 00:35:23.370
As fate would have it.
Mr. Crombie

708
00:35:23.490 --> 00:35:24.830
had been having
similar thoughts.

709
00:35:24.990 --> 00:35:27.330
Ah. but not the means
to put them into action.

710
00:35:27.870 --> 00:35:30.670
I had a small pension to
contribute to his inspiration.

711
00:35:30.830 --> 00:35:33.000
Still. he is modest
in calling us partners.

712
00:35:33.130 --> 00:35:34.880
Mr. Crombie does the work.

713
00:35:35.050 --> 00:35:37.420
I am merely content
to sit at my desk

714
00:35:37.550 --> 00:35:39.130
and help out when I can.

715
00:35:39.300 --> 00:35:40.720
Well. I thank you both.

716
00:35:40.880 --> 00:35:44.720
It seems you've achieved
a-a great deal in our absence.

717
00:35:44.890 --> 00:35:46.520
[Cunningham]
And I thank you. General.

718
00:35:46.680 --> 00:35:47.930
for this place

719
00:35:48.100 --> 00:35:51.060
my mother and I are
so fortunate to call home.

720
00:35:51.230 --> 00:35:54.060
Now. if you'll pardon me.
I was on my way out.

721
00:35:54.190 --> 00:35:56.730
I will accompany you. if I may.

722
00:35:58.740 --> 00:36:00.490
Have you follow me.
Mrs. Fraser.

723
00:36:00.650 --> 00:36:02.200
Yes. actually. Mr. Crombie...

724
00:36:02.360 --> 00:36:03.780
[indistinct chatter]

725
00:36:03.910 --> 00:36:08.250
Captain. I must invite you
to call me Mr. Fraser.

726
00:36:08.700 --> 00:36:10.160
Having resigned my commission

727
00:36:10.330 --> 00:36:12.080
following
the Battle of Monmouth. I...

728
00:36:12.250 --> 00:36:15.210
I have no further association
with the Continental Army.

729
00:36:15.380 --> 00:36:17.050
Well. that's modest
of you. sir.

730
00:36:17.500 --> 00:36:18.880
I've usually found that any man

731
00:36:19.050 --> 00:36:20.920
who's held a military post
of any pretension

732
00:36:21.090 --> 00:36:22.680
clings to his title for life.

733
00:36:22.840 --> 00:36:25.890
[chuckles] No. mine was merely
a temporary appointment.

734
00:36:26.390 --> 00:36:29.770
But I do ken there are many
fine officers who deserve

735
00:36:29.930 --> 00:36:33.480
to retain their titles after
long and honorable service.

736
00:36:34.150 --> 00:36:36.320
I'm sure that's the case
wi' you. Captain.

737
00:36:36.440 --> 00:36:40.570
Well. yes. uh. you are correct
that I'm retired.

738
00:36:41.110 --> 00:36:43.450
though I prefer to retain
the appellation of captain

739
00:36:43.610 --> 00:36:45.120
less as a measure of honor

740
00:36:45.280 --> 00:36:49.410
and more because I've never
much liked the name Charles.

741
00:36:50.250 --> 00:36:51.540
[Jamie chuckles]

742
00:36:51.660 --> 00:36:53.250
Although. in all honesty.
after thirty years

743
00:36:53.420 --> 00:36:54.830
serving in His Majesty's Army.

744
00:36:55.000 --> 00:36:57.130
I suppose I'm simply
used to it.

745
00:36:57.250 --> 00:36:58.750
[chuckles]

746
00:37:01.010 --> 00:37:02.720
You fought for the king. then?

747
00:37:04.260 --> 00:37:05.300
Yes.

748
00:37:05.470 --> 00:37:08.180
But I laid down my sword
for good

749
00:37:08.350 --> 00:37:10.310
after the Battle
of Bemis Heights.

750
00:37:11.600 --> 00:37:14.560
I understand you. too.
were at Saratoga.

751
00:37:16.100 --> 00:37:16.900
Aye.

752
00:37:17.060 --> 00:37:20.030
♪ ♪

753
00:37:22.070 --> 00:37:23.700
And we would have been
on opposite sides

754
00:37:23.860 --> 00:37:25.360
of the same battlefield.

755
00:37:26.160 --> 00:37:27.370
[sighs]

756
00:37:28.030 --> 00:37:30.870
War is a terrible thing.

757
00:37:32.700 --> 00:37:35.790
I am most happy
to be done wi' it.

758
00:37:35.960 --> 00:37:38.920
♪ ♪

759
00:37:41.250 --> 00:37:44.300
How did you come
to settle here on the Ridge?

760
00:37:44.470 --> 00:37:47.050
Ah. like a good many others.
I came to North Carolina

761
00:37:47.180 --> 00:37:48.890
because I had
acquaintances here.

762
00:37:49.050 --> 00:37:51.520
Two of my former officers
are from Salisbury.

763
00:37:51.850 --> 00:37:53.350
I visited their families.

764
00:37:53.520 --> 00:37:56.560
and then I walked until my legs
could carry me no farther.

765
00:37:57.150 --> 00:38:00.650
until I found a place beautiful
enough to bring me some peace.

766
00:38:02.860 --> 00:38:04.570
And here I was.

767
00:38:04.740 --> 00:38:07.660
♪ ♪

768
00:38:12.080 --> 00:38:14.200
[Claire] Cunningham
is a charming fellow.

769
00:38:15.370 --> 00:38:17.790
And he's certainly gained some
influence while we were away.

770
00:38:17.960 --> 00:38:21.960
Ah. Aye. it'd be wise
to ken him better.

771
00:38:22.960 --> 00:38:25.010
That would be
the prudent thing to do...

772
00:38:25.880 --> 00:38:28.010
especially since
he's a redcoat.

773
00:38:29.220 --> 00:38:31.390
He's retired. like me.

774
00:38:31.890 --> 00:38:33.390
Says he's done wi' the war.

775
00:38:34.310 --> 00:38:36.640
I have no reason not to take
the man at his word.

776
00:38:36.810 --> 00:38:38.350
though...

777
00:38:38.520 --> 00:38:40.860
I do wonder if the war
is done with him.

778
00:38:41.020 --> 00:38:42.190
Well. I suppose
someone could wonder

779
00:38:42.360 --> 00:38:43.530
the same thing about you.

780
00:38:43.690 --> 00:38:45.820
[chuckles] Trust me. Sassenach.

781
00:38:46.280 --> 00:38:47.400
I'm done...

782
00:38:47.780 --> 00:38:50.070
whether the war
likes it or no'.

783
00:38:50.240 --> 00:38:51.410
[clicks tongue]

784
00:38:54.910 --> 00:38:56.870
[shell cracking]

785
00:38:58.670 --> 00:38:59.830
[clang]

786
00:39:04.210 --> 00:39:05.710
[spoon clatters]

787
00:39:05.880 --> 00:39:09.180
[William groaning]

788
00:39:10.180 --> 00:39:11.430
[glass thuds]

789
00:39:11.600 --> 00:39:12.720
[Lord John Grey] The hair of the
dog that bit you.

790
00:39:12.890 --> 00:39:14.430
Good God. what is that?

791
00:39:15.180 --> 00:39:16.810
The recipe is proprietary.

792
00:39:17.640 --> 00:39:19.560
but the results
cannot be argued with.

793
00:39:21.190 --> 00:39:22.400
Drink up.

794
00:39:31.620 --> 00:39:33.660
I am due to dine
with General Prévost

795
00:39:33.830 --> 00:39:34.830
in an hour.

796
00:39:35.950 --> 00:39:38.080
Perhaps you'd care
to accompany me?

797
00:39:39.710 --> 00:39:43.500
His cook is far superior
to mine.

798
00:39:44.590 --> 00:39:46.210
And despite
an unfortunate lack of humor.

799
00:39:46.380 --> 00:39:48.260
the man is a decent soldier.

800
00:39:49.170 --> 00:39:50.260
Ambitious.

801
00:39:50.680 --> 00:39:52.140
I know what you are doing.

802
00:39:52.510 --> 00:39:53.850
It will not work.

803
00:39:54.010 --> 00:39:55.350
Frankly. I'm surprised

804
00:39:55.510 --> 00:39:56.930
you're trying to entice me
back into the army.

805
00:39:57.100 --> 00:39:58.230
considering
how opposed you were

806
00:39:58.390 --> 00:39:59.850
to my joining
in the first place.

807
00:39:59.980 --> 00:40:03.770
Idleness and wallowing
do not suit you. William.

808
00:40:07.780 --> 00:40:10.030
And though it was
dreadfully unfortunate.

809
00:40:10.650 --> 00:40:13.160
the British Army
is not to blame

810
00:40:13.620 --> 00:40:15.620
for what happened
to Ms. Pocock.

811
00:40:15.780 --> 00:40:18.580
[pensive music plays]

812
00:40:18.750 --> 00:40:19.910
♪ ♪

813
00:40:20.080 --> 00:40:21.160
No.

814
00:40:22.500 --> 00:40:24.290
I swore to protect her.

815
00:40:25.920 --> 00:40:27.250
I am to blame...

816
00:40:27.420 --> 00:40:29.460
and that devil of a turncoat.
Richardson.

817
00:40:29.590 --> 00:40:32.970
I. too. want Richardson
to pay for his actions.

818
00:40:33.090 --> 00:40:34.300
And he will.

819
00:40:35.600 --> 00:40:37.510
But there are ways
to go about it

820
00:40:37.680 --> 00:40:39.890
that perhaps entail
less drinking oneself

821
00:40:40.060 --> 00:40:42.890
into oblivion
night after night.

822
00:40:45.400 --> 00:40:48.070
Well. if you're truly finished
with the army.

823
00:40:48.230 --> 00:40:50.610
perhaps it is time
you returned to England...

824
00:40:52.030 --> 00:40:55.450
although it would pain me
to part with you again so soon.

825
00:40:56.660 --> 00:40:58.030
You've attained your majority.

826
00:40:58.160 --> 00:40:59.620
and therefore you can manage
your estates.

827
00:40:59.790 --> 00:41:01.450
My steward is doing
a more than adequate job.

828
00:41:01.620 --> 00:41:04.960
Your steward is not the ninth
Earl of Ellesmere. William.

829
00:41:05.130 --> 00:41:08.130
-You are.
-By way of cuckoldry and a lie.

830
00:41:08.300 --> 00:41:09.880
[Lord John]
Well. be that as it may.

831
00:41:10.050 --> 00:41:12.800
your mother was married
to the eighth Earl of Ellesmere

832
00:41:12.970 --> 00:41:14.590
at the time of your birth.

833
00:41:15.720 --> 00:41:17.220
Therefore. the title
is yours by law.

834
00:41:17.390 --> 00:41:19.180
And how does one go about
renouncing a title?

835
00:41:19.350 --> 00:41:20.350
You cannot.

836
00:41:20.770 --> 00:41:21.730
You mean I shall not.

837
00:41:21.850 --> 00:41:23.560
No. you cannot!

838
00:41:23.730 --> 00:41:26.690
♪ ♪

839
00:41:28.060 --> 00:41:32.320
A peerage is the gift
of a grateful monarch.

840
00:41:33.030 --> 00:41:35.450
There are no means set down
in law for renouncing it.

841
00:41:35.820 --> 00:41:37.120
A monarch
who ceases to be grateful

842
00:41:37.240 --> 00:41:38.660
can strip a peer of his title.

843
00:41:38.830 --> 00:41:40.370
though the only grounds
for that which come to mind

844
00:41:40.540 --> 00:41:42.870
are engaging in rebellion
against the crown.

845
00:41:44.870 --> 00:41:45.960
Treason.

846
00:41:46.120 --> 00:41:47.250
Betrayal of your king
and country

847
00:41:47.420 --> 00:41:48.670
hardly seems like
a suitable means

848
00:41:48.840 --> 00:41:50.750
of solving
your personal difficulties.

849
00:41:51.960 --> 00:41:54.010
It might be easier...

850
00:41:54.590 --> 00:41:57.680
to ask what you want to do.

851
00:41:58.600 --> 00:42:01.850
rather than asking
how not to do what you don't.

852
00:42:01.970 --> 00:42:03.770
It might be easier
to know what I want to do

853
00:42:03.930 --> 00:42:05.560
if I knew who I bloody was.

854
00:42:05.690 --> 00:42:08.310
♪ ♪

855
00:42:08.440 --> 00:42:10.770
At a certain point.
I suppose it is up to you

856
00:42:10.940 --> 00:42:15.200
to decide who you want to be
and to act accordingly.

857
00:42:19.160 --> 00:42:20.240
Whether you choose

858
00:42:20.410 --> 00:42:23.250
to call yourself Ransom.
Fraser. or Grey.

859
00:42:23.410 --> 00:42:25.710
no man with any claim
to your parentage

860
00:42:25.870 --> 00:42:29.000
would tolerate the way you
treated Lady Grey yesterday.

861
00:42:30.040 --> 00:42:33.510
That is something
I insist you remedy.

862
00:42:33.670 --> 00:42:36.680
♪ ♪

863
00:42:42.560 --> 00:42:44.140
[bees buzzing]

864
00:42:44.270 --> 00:42:46.730
I canna say bees are the most
traditional homecoming gift.

865
00:42:46.850 --> 00:42:48.980
but it's very thoughtful
of ye. Lizzie.

866
00:42:49.440 --> 00:42:52.150
Well. I've always wanted
my own hive. so thank you.

867
00:42:52.270 --> 00:42:55.030
We'll. uh. build
a proper home for them

868
00:42:55.190 --> 00:42:57.360
some safe distance
from the house.

869
00:42:57.530 --> 00:42:58.990
I'm so glad
to have you both back.

870
00:42:59.160 --> 00:43:00.700
[Jamie] As soon as there's
a fresh bit of honey.

871
00:43:00.870 --> 00:43:05.370
we'll bring some over for you
and Kezzie and Josiah.

872
00:43:05.540 --> 00:43:06.750
[Lizzie chuckles]

873
00:43:06.910 --> 00:43:09.370
[chuckles] So lovely
to see you again. Lizzie.

874
00:43:09.540 --> 00:43:14.420
and so good to meet you.
my little namesake. wee Claire.

875
00:43:14.590 --> 00:43:17.130
[chuckles] Go to Mama.

876
00:43:18.800 --> 00:43:20.680
We'll see you both again soon.

877
00:43:20.840 --> 00:43:21.930
Aye.

878
00:43:23.680 --> 00:43:26.810
Bees--
very sociable and curious.

879
00:43:26.980 --> 00:43:30.400
which only makes sense.
going back and forth all day.

880
00:43:30.560 --> 00:43:32.190
sharing news wi' their pollen.

881
00:43:33.020 --> 00:43:35.070
-That's one way to put it.
-Hmm.

882
00:43:35.190 --> 00:43:38.240
Did ye ken that bees are
the link between our world

883
00:43:38.400 --> 00:43:39.610
and the spirit world?

884
00:43:39.780 --> 00:43:42.740
That's why ye tell them
what's happening.

885
00:43:43.580 --> 00:43:44.740
-You do?
-Aye.

886
00:43:45.540 --> 00:43:48.580
If someone should come to visit
or a new bairn should be born

887
00:43:48.750 --> 00:43:51.580
or a settler
should depart or die.

888
00:43:51.750 --> 00:43:53.130
you dinna tell the bees.
they'll take offense.

889
00:43:53.290 --> 00:43:55.090
and all of them
will just fly away.

890
00:43:55.880 --> 00:43:57.840
We can't have that.
then. can we?

891
00:43:58.010 --> 00:43:59.130
[chuckles]

892
00:43:59.720 --> 00:44:02.550
[light music plays]

893
00:44:02.720 --> 00:44:05.760
♪ ♪

894
00:44:18.110 --> 00:44:19.650
[Roger] Hello. the house!

895
00:44:20.030 --> 00:44:22.860
[sentimental music plays]

896
00:44:23.030 --> 00:44:25.950
♪ ♪

897
00:44:39.130 --> 00:44:40.300
Ah!

898
00:44:41.170 --> 00:44:43.390
Oh. Oh.

899
00:44:43.550 --> 00:44:44.890
[Jemmy] Grandda!

900
00:44:45.050 --> 00:44:47.310
[laughing]
Jeremiah. you've grown so tall.

901
00:44:47.470 --> 00:44:48.430
[Jemmy] Grandda!

902
00:44:48.600 --> 00:44:50.850
That's your granny and grandpa.

903
00:44:52.770 --> 00:44:54.650
[crying] Is it really you?

904
00:44:55.310 --> 00:44:56.440
God. I've missed you.

905
00:44:56.610 --> 00:44:59.480
-Oh. darling.
-[laughter]

906
00:45:01.570 --> 00:45:03.150
This is Mandy.

907
00:45:03.610 --> 00:45:04.860
Mandy.

908
00:45:06.200 --> 00:45:07.580
Look at you.

909
00:45:07.740 --> 00:45:08.870
[Jamie] I canna believe it.

910
00:45:09.040 --> 00:45:10.620
We never thought
we'd see you again.

911
00:45:11.000 --> 00:45:13.870
-What are you doing here?
-We wanted to come home.

912
00:45:14.040 --> 00:45:16.670
[laughter]

913
00:45:17.340 --> 00:45:18.710
Jem.

914
00:45:18.880 --> 00:45:21.710
[laughing] Roger. Oh.

915
00:45:21.880 --> 00:45:24.880
It doesna matter now. lass.
You're here.

916
00:45:26.010 --> 00:45:28.510
-We all are.
-[laughter]

917
00:45:30.810 --> 00:45:33.810
♪ ♪

918
00:45:37.610 --> 00:45:40.280
Our house is yer house.
Ye ken that well enough.

919
00:45:40.820 --> 00:45:43.820
Ye can stay here till we build
you one of yer own.

920
00:45:44.450 --> 00:45:46.700
-[Fanny] You're very pretty.
-[Mandy] Thank you.

921
00:45:47.530 --> 00:45:49.450
Fanny is so sweet with Mandy.

922
00:45:50.660 --> 00:45:52.200
How did she come to be
living with you?

923
00:45:52.370 --> 00:45:55.580
Oh. she's a wee orphan lass.

924
00:45:56.460 --> 00:45:59.170
Your brother took her
under his protection.

925
00:45:59.340 --> 00:46:00.800
entrusted her to us.

926
00:46:00.960 --> 00:46:01.880
William?

927
00:46:02.920 --> 00:46:04.920
Does that mean he knows
that you're his father?

928
00:46:05.550 --> 00:46:06.760
He does.

929
00:46:08.180 --> 00:46:09.470
[Brianna] Ah.

930
00:46:09.640 --> 00:46:10.970
Take it he's not too happy
about that.

931
00:46:11.140 --> 00:46:12.560
Doesn't appear so.

932
00:46:13.930 --> 00:46:14.930
Give him time.

933
00:46:22.440 --> 00:46:24.820
[Mandy] Mummy. read me a story.

934
00:46:25.650 --> 00:46:27.660
Uh. what's the magic word?

935
00:46:27.820 --> 00:46:28.950
[Mandy] Please?

936
00:46:29.990 --> 00:46:31.330
What do you think?

937
00:46:32.620 --> 00:46:33.660
Why not?

938
00:46:34.370 --> 00:46:35.790
-[Brianna] Go get him.
-[Jamie chuckles]

939
00:46:35.960 --> 00:46:37.330
Ye brought a book
for the bairns.

940
00:46:37.500 --> 00:46:39.460
Read to me. Grandda. please?

941
00:46:39.630 --> 00:46:41.380
[Jamie] Ah. all right.

942
00:46:43.090 --> 00:46:45.260
[sighs] Let's see.

943
00:46:45.920 --> 00:46:48.800
[chuckles. clears throat]

944
00:46:48.970 --> 00:46:51.850
[light music plays]

945
00:46:52.010 --> 00:46:53.010
Oh.

946
00:46:53.180 --> 00:46:54.930
It's like a painting.

947
00:46:55.980 --> 00:46:56.980
Eh.

948
00:46:57.390 --> 00:47:00.270
♪ ♪

949
00:47:00.440 --> 00:47:03.860
"In the great green room.

950
00:47:04.030 --> 00:47:07.070
"there was a telephone
and a red balloon

951
00:47:07.240 --> 00:47:08.820
"and a picture of...

952
00:47:09.490 --> 00:47:11.570
the cow jumping over the moon."

953
00:47:11.740 --> 00:47:13.160
[chuckles]

954
00:47:13.330 --> 00:47:16.620
Eh. yeah. "and-and-and
there were three little bears

955
00:47:16.790 --> 00:47:18.160
sitting on chairs."

956
00:47:18.290 --> 00:47:19.960
Well. a bear's likely to eat
a chair than sit on one.

957
00:47:20.120 --> 00:47:23.170
and all three of them together
make a meal

958
00:47:23.340 --> 00:47:26.010
of anyone close by
wanting to count 'em.

959
00:47:26.170 --> 00:47:28.840
[all chuckling]

960
00:47:29.010 --> 00:47:32.050
A lovely bit of nonsense.
I feel like I ken it.

961
00:47:32.220 --> 00:47:34.810
Because I told you
about it years ago.

962
00:47:35.220 --> 00:47:36.640
when we were on a ship
to Jamaica

963
00:47:36.770 --> 00:47:38.640
-and I was missing Bree.
-Mm.

964
00:47:38.770 --> 00:47:40.310
Why don't you all go
and finish the book

965
00:47:40.440 --> 00:47:43.230
in the other room
while the adults chat. hmm?

966
00:47:43.980 --> 00:47:45.900
Jem. you can read it to them.

967
00:47:46.030 --> 00:47:47.940
♪ ♪

968
00:47:48.110 --> 00:47:49.490
I hope it's all right
Fanny saw that book.

969
00:47:49.650 --> 00:47:51.030
She won't know
it's modern. will she?

970
00:47:51.200 --> 00:47:53.320
Oh. she's certainly never
seen anything like it.

971
00:47:53.450 --> 00:47:54.990
But I'm sure it's fine.

972
00:47:55.450 --> 00:47:57.870
This one is for you.

973
00:47:59.040 --> 00:48:00.710
-[Claire] Oh. Bree.
-[Brianna] Mm.

974
00:48:00.830 --> 00:48:01.830
Oh.

975
00:48:02.420 --> 00:48:03.540
Oh. it's marvelous.

976
00:48:03.710 --> 00:48:05.960
Let me see. mo nighean donn.

977
00:48:06.840 --> 00:48:09.050
-[Claire chuckles]
-[Jamie] Hmm.

978
00:48:11.180 --> 00:48:13.930
The Merck Manual.
13th edition--

979
00:48:14.100 --> 00:48:15.310
popular writer.

980
00:48:15.470 --> 00:48:17.600
Either that or he's made
a devil lot of mistakes.

981
00:48:17.770 --> 00:48:19.770
-It's a medical book.
-[Jamie] Mm.

982
00:48:19.930 --> 00:48:22.350
"Controlling the spread
of E. histolytica

983
00:48:22.480 --> 00:48:26.940
requires prevention of access
of human feces to the mouth."

984
00:48:27.110 --> 00:48:28.320
Mm.

985
00:48:28.480 --> 00:48:31.030
It's. uh. what folk
have learned about healing.

986
00:48:31.150 --> 00:48:32.820
I'm guessing you ken
not to eat shite.

987
00:48:32.990 --> 00:48:35.240
-[laughter]
-Yes. darling.

988
00:48:36.280 --> 00:48:37.790
I can't begin to imagine

989
00:48:37.950 --> 00:48:39.620
what they've discovered
since I left.

990
00:48:39.790 --> 00:48:42.250
And I think you will like
this one. Da.

991
00:48:42.420 --> 00:48:43.370
[Jamie] Ah.

992
00:48:46.420 --> 00:48:48.380
-You like it?
-Thank you.

993
00:48:50.130 --> 00:48:52.130
Frodo Baggins.

994
00:48:52.300 --> 00:48:54.090
Eh. a Welshman.

995
00:48:54.260 --> 00:48:56.050
[laughs] No.

996
00:48:56.220 --> 00:48:57.640
-Not--not exactly.
-Ah.

997
00:48:57.810 --> 00:49:00.980
That's one of Jem's favorites--
mine too. actually.

998
00:49:01.810 --> 00:49:03.650
I think the tale
might speak to you.

999
00:49:03.980 --> 00:49:05.230
Thank you kindly.

1000
00:49:06.060 --> 00:49:08.900
[pensive music plays]

1001
00:49:09.030 --> 00:49:12.070
♪ ♪

1002
00:49:17.330 --> 00:49:20.910
Are you a minister. Roger Mac.

1003
00:49:21.040 --> 00:49:22.540
-in the future?
-Hmm.

1004
00:49:23.580 --> 00:49:24.830
No.

1005
00:49:25.250 --> 00:49:26.670
No. I was. uh--

1006
00:49:27.380 --> 00:49:30.460
I was so full of doubt
after everything that happened.

1007
00:49:31.630 --> 00:49:34.180
But. uh. well.
now that we're back...

1008
00:49:34.340 --> 00:49:38.180
Whatever you decide. new folk
have settled on the Ridge

1009
00:49:38.350 --> 00:49:39.510
since you left.

1010
00:49:39.680 --> 00:49:41.520
You should go about.
introduce yourself.

1011
00:49:44.390 --> 00:49:47.440
There's a man by the name
of Cunningham.

1012
00:49:47.940 --> 00:49:49.730
He helped open
the new trading post.

1013
00:49:50.230 --> 00:49:52.740
I'd be curious to ken
what ye might think of him.

1014
00:49:53.360 --> 00:49:55.070
anything ye might learn.

1015
00:49:56.070 --> 00:49:56.990
Aye.

1016
00:49:57.490 --> 00:49:58.740
[Brianna] She was
on antibiotics for a while.

1017
00:49:58.910 --> 00:50:00.580
had a few checkups.
but other than that...

1018
00:50:00.740 --> 00:50:02.540
Children are remarkable.

1019
00:50:02.700 --> 00:50:04.160
Listening to her heart.
you'd never have known

1020
00:50:04.330 --> 00:50:05.330
anything was wrong.

1021
00:50:05.500 --> 00:50:06.870
[Brianna]
Kids are finally asleep.

1022
00:50:07.040 --> 00:50:08.380
Thank God.

1023
00:50:08.500 --> 00:50:11.210
I still canna believe it.
the sight of you here.

1024
00:50:12.210 --> 00:50:14.170
We weren't even sure
if the letters would reach ye

1025
00:50:14.340 --> 00:50:16.010
when we left them at the bank.

1026
00:50:16.800 --> 00:50:20.850
There was a--well. uh.
an inheritance. I suppose.

1027
00:50:21.390 --> 00:50:23.100
We thought you should ken
what had become of us.

1028
00:50:23.640 --> 00:50:25.180
We'd never have dreamed
you'd have used them

1029
00:50:25.350 --> 00:50:26.690
to find your way back to us.

1030
00:50:29.610 --> 00:50:30.610
To coming home.

1031
00:50:31.070 --> 00:50:32.690
-To family.
-[glasses clinking]

1032
00:50:32.860 --> 00:50:33.990
Slainté.

1033
00:50:39.570 --> 00:50:41.160
I. uh... [clears throat]

1034
00:50:41.660 --> 00:50:43.200
...I brought back another book.

1035
00:50:44.290 --> 00:50:46.660
I didn't want to show it
in front of the kids. but...

1036
00:50:48.460 --> 00:50:51.750
[pensive music plays]

1037
00:50:51.920 --> 00:50:53.460
Soul of a Rebel:

1038
00:50:54.170 --> 00:50:56.970
Scottish Roots
of the American Revolution

1039
00:50:57.130 --> 00:50:59.890
by Franklin W. Randall. PhD.

1040
00:51:01.720 --> 00:51:05.180
[sighs] Um. it's the research
Daddy was doing before he died.

1041
00:51:05.640 --> 00:51:08.270
It was published
after we had both left.

1042
00:51:09.230 --> 00:51:10.690
Did ye find it useful?

1043
00:51:11.230 --> 00:51:12.980
I started to open it. but...

1044
00:51:13.480 --> 00:51:15.030
I couldn't even get
past the jacket.

1045
00:51:15.490 --> 00:51:17.360
I knew that if I read it.
it would.

1046
00:51:17.530 --> 00:51:19.910
uh. feel like
losing him all over again.

1047
00:51:20.070 --> 00:51:22.580
Same with your letters.
actually.

1048
00:51:23.120 --> 00:51:25.040
We. uh--we spaced them out.

1049
00:51:25.200 --> 00:51:27.620
because as long as there were
still unopened ones.

1050
00:51:28.750 --> 00:51:30.250
you were still alive.

1051
00:51:30.420 --> 00:51:33.130
♪ ♪

1052
00:51:33.250 --> 00:51:35.210
Something must have happened...

1053
00:51:36.050 --> 00:51:39.930
for you to come back
middle of a war.

1054
00:51:40.220 --> 00:51:41.260
Aye...

1055
00:51:42.300 --> 00:51:43.850
something happened.

1056
00:51:44.510 --> 00:51:45.720
A lot of things.

1057
00:51:47.980 --> 00:51:49.230
I suppose. uh.

1058
00:51:49.940 --> 00:51:52.770
there's something
we need to tell you. too...

1059
00:51:54.320 --> 00:51:57.490
about Fanny and your sister...

1060
00:51:58.280 --> 00:51:59.610
Faith.

1061
00:51:59.780 --> 00:52:01.610
♪ ♪

1062
00:52:01.780 --> 00:52:04.700
[birds chirping]

1063
00:52:09.710 --> 00:52:11.080
[exhales sharply]

1064
00:52:24.100 --> 00:52:26.430
Lady Grey.
I owe you an apology.

1065
00:52:27.810 --> 00:52:29.350
When you first came
upon me yesterday.

1066
00:52:29.520 --> 00:52:32.140
I'd only just learned
of my cousin's passing.

1067
00:52:33.690 --> 00:52:34.770
I was in shock.

1068
00:52:35.360 --> 00:52:38.320
Still. that is no excuse
for my ungentlemanly behavior.

1069
00:52:39.530 --> 00:52:41.450
I beg your forgiveness for it.

1070
00:52:43.910 --> 00:52:47.580
Well. I suppose I was not
altogether kind either.

1071
00:52:47.740 --> 00:52:49.830
I tend to have rather
a sharp tongue when piqued.

1072
00:52:50.000 --> 00:52:51.580
You had every reason.

1073
00:52:59.340 --> 00:53:01.220
We did marry rather in haste.

1074
00:53:02.090 --> 00:53:04.390
Benjamin wrote to tell
his father of the union.

1075
00:53:04.510 --> 00:53:06.970
but the letter appears
to have gone astray. so...

1076
00:53:07.720 --> 00:53:09.220
I suppose a modicum
of skepticism

1077
00:53:09.390 --> 00:53:10.930
is to be expected.

1078
00:53:11.980 --> 00:53:13.600
You have my deepest sympathies

1079
00:53:13.770 --> 00:53:15.400
on the loss
of your husband. madam.

1080
00:53:15.770 --> 00:53:16.650
Thank you.

1081
00:53:17.730 --> 00:53:20.360
And you. on the loss
of your cousin.

1082
00:53:22.030 --> 00:53:23.150
I beg your pardon.

1083
00:53:23.320 --> 00:53:24.820
I'm a bit overcome
with emotion.

1084
00:53:24.990 --> 00:53:27.740
Quite understandable.
given the circumstances.

1085
00:53:27.910 --> 00:53:30.200
[baby babbling]

1086
00:53:30.370 --> 00:53:33.330
Hmm. [chuckles]
Oh. he likes being outside.

1087
00:53:34.080 --> 00:53:37.130
-[baby fusses]
-Fresh air calms him.

1088
00:53:38.500 --> 00:53:40.840
[baby squeals happily]

1089
00:53:42.130 --> 00:53:44.050
He looks quite like Benjamin.

1090
00:53:47.800 --> 00:53:50.140
I hope I don't give you pain
by saying so.

1091
00:53:51.270 --> 00:53:51.930
No.

1092
00:53:53.520 --> 00:53:57.520
No. it's a reminder
of the love that bore him.

1093
00:53:58.060 --> 00:54:00.110
I suppose
that's some consolation.

1094
00:54:00.270 --> 00:54:02.280
[sentimental music plays]

1095
00:54:02.440 --> 00:54:03.950
I do not have any siblings.

1096
00:54:04.570 --> 00:54:07.160
Ben and Henry were
like brothers to me.

1097
00:54:08.120 --> 00:54:09.780
He said as much about you.

1098
00:54:10.700 --> 00:54:13.330
And. perhaps.
when Trevor is older.

1099
00:54:14.160 --> 00:54:17.460
you can tell him
of his father. man-to-man.

1100
00:54:17.630 --> 00:54:20.460
♪ ♪

1101
00:54:20.630 --> 00:54:23.090
It pains me that
he'll have no memory of him...

1102
00:54:25.010 --> 00:54:27.260
...no knowledge of who
he was in the world.

1103
00:54:29.050 --> 00:54:31.260
[William chuckles]

1104
00:54:31.430 --> 00:54:34.020
♪ ♪

1105
00:54:34.180 --> 00:54:37.850
I promise. I shall do
all I can for Trevor...

1106
00:54:40.110 --> 00:54:42.480
...and for you. Lady Grey.

1107
00:54:42.650 --> 00:54:45.860
♪ ♪

1108
00:54:46.030 --> 00:54:47.820
[gunshot. animal squeaks]

1109
00:54:49.780 --> 00:54:53.490
[Jamie] This Robert Cameron
read our letters. ye said.

1110
00:54:53.660 --> 00:54:55.000
[Brianna] Yes.

1111
00:54:55.160 --> 00:54:56.580
[Jamie] Then he not only kens
about the Jacobite gold.

1112
00:54:56.710 --> 00:55:00.670
but he knows where we live.
when we live.

1113
00:55:01.420 --> 00:55:03.210
What's to stop him
coming after you?

1114
00:55:03.800 --> 00:55:06.510
Nothing. if he can time-travel.

1115
00:55:07.590 --> 00:55:10.510
But if he could. then
why hasn't he done it already?

1116
00:55:11.390 --> 00:55:14.220
No sane man canna guess
the mind of a mad one.

1117
00:55:16.230 --> 00:55:17.440
[sighing] Well...

1118
00:55:17.600 --> 00:55:19.940
we figured if no time
is completely safe.

1119
00:55:20.100 --> 00:55:21.730
then we'd rather
all be together.

1120
00:55:22.860 --> 00:55:25.190
I canna believe
I put wee Jeremiah in danger.

1121
00:55:25.360 --> 00:55:27.820
As soon as we're back at
the house. I'll move the gold.

1122
00:55:27.990 --> 00:55:29.950
That way.
if Cameron does come looking.

1123
00:55:30.070 --> 00:55:34.040
he'll have no way to find it.
save through me.

1124
00:55:37.290 --> 00:55:38.710
[Brianna] My God.

1125
00:55:38.870 --> 00:55:41.750
[dramatic music plays]

1126
00:55:41.920 --> 00:55:44.880
♪ ♪

1127
00:55:49.340 --> 00:55:52.510
I know there are brands
for thieves. but what is GR?

1128
00:55:52.930 --> 00:55:54.310
George Rex.

1129
00:55:55.850 --> 00:55:57.140
King George.

1130
00:55:58.600 --> 00:56:00.810
These men were hanged
for being Loyalists?

1131
00:56:02.610 --> 00:56:05.360
There are devils
on both sides of this war.

1132
00:56:05.860 --> 00:56:08.900
♪ ♪

1133
00:56:19.250 --> 00:56:20.790
Where is your father. child?

1134
00:56:20.960 --> 00:56:22.880
I don't know.
This is Esmerelda.

1135
00:56:23.000 --> 00:56:24.090
Eh.

1136
00:56:24.250 --> 00:56:26.380
I wish to speak to your father.

1137
00:56:26.550 --> 00:56:27.920
[Mandy] Look...

1138
00:56:28.090 --> 00:56:30.550
♪ Frère Jacques.
Frère Jacques ♪

1139
00:56:30.720 --> 00:56:33.090
-♪ Dormez-vous? Dormez-vous? ♪
-Stop that.

1140
00:56:33.260 --> 00:56:35.680
-Look at me.
-Why?

1141
00:56:36.100 --> 00:56:38.850
You are
a very impertinent child.

1142
00:56:39.480 --> 00:56:41.520
And your father
should beat you.

1143
00:56:41.690 --> 00:56:44.310
You look like the Wicked Witch.
Fly away on your broom.

1144
00:56:44.480 --> 00:56:46.440
[gasps]
What in the name of perdition

1145
00:56:46.610 --> 00:56:47.780
do you mean by that?

1146
00:56:47.940 --> 00:56:49.190
You wicked child!

1147
00:56:49.320 --> 00:56:51.990
Fly away on your broom.
you mean old lady.

1148
00:56:52.570 --> 00:56:54.320
Aah! That really hurt.

1149
00:56:54.490 --> 00:56:57.240
♪ ♪

1150
00:56:57.410 --> 00:56:58.540
Leave my house.

1151
00:56:58.700 --> 00:56:59.580
The girl spoke
to me rudely. sir.

1152
00:56:59.750 --> 00:57:01.250
and I will not have it.

1153
00:57:01.410 --> 00:57:03.620
Evidently. no one has sought
to discipline her correctly.

1154
00:57:03.790 --> 00:57:04.670
so no wonder.

1155
00:57:04.830 --> 00:57:06.420
Speaking of rudeness.

1156
00:57:06.880 --> 00:57:09.170
I don't believe I've had
the honor of your acquaintance.

1157
00:57:09.920 --> 00:57:11.220
I'm Claire Fraser.

1158
00:57:13.050 --> 00:57:15.800
My son mentioned
you were looking for this.

1159
00:57:15.970 --> 00:57:18.930
♪ ♪

1160
00:57:25.480 --> 00:57:29.610
You are all undoubtedly
going to hell.

1161
00:57:29.730 --> 00:57:32.780
♪ ♪

1162
00:57:39.450 --> 00:57:40.700
Who the devil was that?

1163
00:57:40.870 --> 00:57:43.460
The Wicked Witch of the West.
I hate her.

1164
00:57:43.620 --> 00:57:44.710
Hmm.

1165
00:57:46.130 --> 00:57:49.170
Oh. Jesus H. Roosevelt Christ.

1166
00:57:50.090 --> 00:57:52.800
[sighs]
She's brought me Jesuit bark.

1167
00:57:52.970 --> 00:57:54.130
Well. in that case.

1168
00:57:54.590 --> 00:57:57.970
I think perhaps that witch
was Mrs. Cunningham.

1169
00:57:58.100 --> 00:58:01.100
♪ ♪

1170
00:58:06.400 --> 00:58:09.020
[distant bird calling]

1171
00:58:17.160 --> 00:58:19.780
[Randall] Is it my face you see
looming in the darkness?

1172
00:58:27.040 --> 00:58:30.290
Why'd ye not tell me
that Frank Randall

1173
00:58:31.000 --> 00:58:32.210
looked like Black Jack?

1174
00:58:34.470 --> 00:58:35.420
[sighs]

1175
00:58:37.010 --> 00:58:39.930
I haven't thought about that
in a very long time.

1176
00:58:41.140 --> 00:58:44.520
[sighs] I-I remember being
startled by the resemblance.

1177
00:58:44.680 --> 00:58:45.730
but...

1178
00:58:46.140 --> 00:58:48.100
once I was acquainted
with Black Jack.

1179
00:58:48.690 --> 00:58:50.310
that quickly wore off...

1180
00:58:52.230 --> 00:58:54.150
because they were so different.

1181
00:58:57.950 --> 00:58:59.570
Ye should have told me.

1182
00:59:01.910 --> 00:59:04.250
I suppose I should have. but--

1183
00:59:04.410 --> 00:59:07.870
but at first. how could
I have explained that to you?

1184
00:59:09.330 --> 00:59:11.000
And then after. well. I--

1185
00:59:11.420 --> 00:59:12.840
I didn't know how.

1186
00:59:14.300 --> 00:59:15.340
[sighs]

1187
00:59:15.510 --> 00:59:17.470
I thought
you might have been upset

1188
00:59:18.180 --> 00:59:19.890
that I had married someone

1189
00:59:20.050 --> 00:59:22.810
who looked so much like
Black Jack Randall.

1190
00:59:22.970 --> 00:59:24.600
I might have been upset.

1191
00:59:25.890 --> 00:59:27.640
There'd have been no point.

1192
00:59:31.900 --> 00:59:33.730
You are mine.

1193
00:59:34.280 --> 00:59:35.820
[chuckles]

1194
00:59:45.450 --> 00:59:47.450
Was he an honest man?

1195
00:59:48.160 --> 00:59:49.250
Frank?

1196
00:59:50.710 --> 00:59:52.170
For the most part.

1197
00:59:52.840 --> 00:59:56.010
He kept secrets.
but then again. so did I.

1198
00:59:56.510 --> 00:59:57.970
Can I trust him. do ye think?

1199
01:00:00.760 --> 01:00:03.640
-About what he's written?
-He was an historian.

1200
01:00:05.010 --> 01:00:07.680
He wouldn't write something
that he knew to be false.

1201
01:00:07.810 --> 01:00:08.850
Why?

1202
01:00:10.480 --> 01:00:12.270
Because he mentions my name.

1203
01:00:13.270 --> 01:00:16.230
Fourteen times so far.

1204
01:00:16.400 --> 01:00:19.320
♪ ♪

1205
01:00:19.450 --> 01:00:21.070
You're in the book?

1206
01:00:22.160 --> 01:00:23.120
Aye.

1207
01:00:24.620 --> 01:00:26.160
What does it say?

1208
01:00:27.080 --> 01:00:29.000
That war is coming
to the backcountry.

1209
01:00:29.160 --> 01:00:31.920
He says there'll be a battle
in about a year's time

1210
01:00:32.080 --> 01:00:34.210
at a place called
King's Mountain...

1211
01:00:35.170 --> 01:00:38.380
and that James Fraser
dies in it.

1212
01:00:38.550 --> 01:00:41.430
[dramatic music plays]

1213
01:00:41.590 --> 01:00:44.600
♪ ♪
